COVID19 Basic Time Series Analysis

COVID19 Basic Time Series Analysis

This analysis is based on data collected and publish Jonh Hopkins University as of April 3rd 2020. The data can be downloaded from the following github web page.

https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19

There have been multiple approaches to hanlding the Coronavirus Crisis around the world. The following analysis shows in a graphical manner the outcomes by country/region over the last several weeks. It provides evidence of what type of approach is more effective and what are the actions that individuals, communities and government should take to control the spread of the virus.

The first section compares regions around the world and how they first addressed the first days of the pandemic. China will be treated as its own region. Selected countries, with good data quality, will be used as reference.

In the next section we will review the mortality rate by country. The rate by confirmed case is documented by John Hopkins Universtiy in the following web site:

https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/data/mortality

There is great variability, most likely because there is great variability in testing. I will review the cases for several countries to find parameters that allow to calculate the most likely number of infections based on number of deaths.

#Create a function that takes the Dataframe for Confirmed Cases and Deaths
#in the Timeseries format provided by John Hopkins in the Global format
#Returns a Dataframe to use in Ggplot that 

Estimated.Infections.Country <- function(Confirm, Death , Country.Terr, State=NA, Lag=14 , Mortality=0.01){
  # Have to add checks in the future. Currently it works with Exact Matches
  library(reshape2)
  
  if (is.na(State)){
    Country.Confirmed = Confirm[Confirm$Country.Region == Country.Terr,]
    Country.Deaths = Death[Death$Country.Region == Country.Terr,]
  }else {
    Country.Confirmed = Confirm[Confirm$Country.Region == Country.Terr & Confirm$Province.State == State,]
    Country.Deaths = Death[Death$Country.Region == Country.Terr & Death$Province.State == State,]
  }

  #confirmed transform into long format
  Country.Confirmed$Statistic = "Confirmed"
  
  Country.Confirmed.Long = reshape(Country.Confirmed,varying = colnames(Country.Confirmed[,5:(dim(Country.Confirmed)[2]-1)]),v.names="Confirmed",idvar=c("Province.State","Country.Region","Lat","Long","Statistic"),direction="long")
  #Add corresponding date to Count
  Country.Confirmed.Long$Date_Name = colnames(Country.Confirmed[,5:(dim(Country.Confirmed)[2]-1)])
  
  #create Dataframe for Deaths. Transform into long format
  
  
  
  Country.Deaths$Statistic = "Deaths"
  Country.Deaths.Long = reshape(Country.Deaths,varying = colnames(Country.Deaths[,5:(dim(Country.Deaths)[2]-1)]),v.names="Deaths",idvar=c("Province.State","Country.Region","Lat","Long","Statistic"),direction="long")
  
  #Add corresponding date to Count
  Country.Deaths.Long$Date_Name = colnames(Country.Deaths[,5:(dim(Country.Deaths)[2]-1)])
  Country.Deaths.Long$Estimated_Infections = NA
  #Deaths is a 14 lag to infections. 1% Mortality rate. Have to start from row 15
  ##Maximum Lag will be 14
  if (Lag >15 ) Lag=14
  #Have to add limits to morality rate >0 and <=1
  Country.Deaths.Long[c(1:(dim(Country.Deaths.Long)[1]-Lag)),"Estimated_Infections"] = Country.Deaths.Long[c((Lag+1):dim(Country.Deaths.Long)[1]),"Deaths"]*(1/Mortality)
  
  #merge deaths and confirmed
  
  Country = merge(Country.Confirmed.Long,Country.Deaths.Long[,c("Date_Name","Deaths","Estimated_Infections")],by="Date_Name")
  Country = Country[order(Country$time),]
  
  #add dates in right format. Convert Date_Name
  
  Country$Date = as.Date(substr(Country$Date_Name,2,nchar(Country$Date_Name)),format ="%m.%d.%y")
  #change  for ggplot
  
  Country.Long = melt(Country[c("Date","Confirmed","Deaths","Estimated_Infections")],id="Date")
  #update names
  colnames(Country.Long) = c("Date","Statistic","Count")
  #calculate linear regression with last 5 values of Estimated infections
  Est.Infect.reduced = Country.Long[Country.Long$Statistic=="Estimated_Infections",c("Date","Count")]
  #only 5 values prior to NA
  temp = min(which(is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count)))
  
  lm.infect = lm(Count ~ Date, data=Est.Infect.reduced[c((temp-5):(temp-1)),])
  #predict for missing dates and append to Es.Infect.reduced
  
  #predict based on 5 last records and add to NAs as probable number of  infections. Directly to 
  
  #predict(lm.infect,newdata=data.frame(Date=Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"]))
  #Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"] = predict(lm.infect,newdata=data.frame(Date=Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"]))
  Country.Long[Country.Long$Statistic=="Estimated_Infections" & is.na(Country.Long$Count),"Count"] = predict(lm.infect,newdata=data.frame(Date=Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"]))
  
  return(Country.Long)
  
}

#check with 


#Example with South Korea and Germany - 1% Mortaliy rate and 14 day lag of Number of Death to Estimated Infections
Country.Long = Estimated.Infections.Country(Confirmed,Deaths,"Korea, South")
ggplot(Country.Long, aes(x= Date, y= Count, group=Statistic )) +   geom_point(aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + theme(legend.position="bottom") + labs(title="COVID19- South Korea - Deaths, Confirmed Cases, Estimated Infections - Assumed Mortality rate 1% \n Estimated Infections over last 14 days based on Linear Regression", y="Count", x="Days", caption="Data Source for confirmed cases and deaths: John Hopkins Hospital")

Country.Long = Estimated.Infections.Country(Confirmed,Deaths,"Germany")
ggplot(Country.Long, aes(x= Date, y= Count, group=Statistic )) +   geom_point(aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + theme(legend.position="bottom") + labs(title="COVID19- Germany - Deaths, Confirmed Cases, Estimated Infections - Assumed Mortality rate 1% \n Estimated Infections over last 14 days based on Linear Regression", y="Count", x="Days", caption="Data Source for confirmed cases and deaths: John Hopkins Hospital")

The following code provides Trellis view of varying Mortality rates from 1% to 1.4% ; and the Lag from 10 to 14 days This will be done for Germany and South Korea which have large populations and have done extensive testing. The number of confirmed cases should track close to the Estimated Infections.

# Charts for South, Korea

mortality = c(0.01, .011, .012, .013, .014)
lag = c(14,13, 12, 11, 10)
#Initialize with first case
Korea.Long = Estimated.Infections.Country(Confirmed,Deaths,"Korea, South",NA,lag[1],mortality[1])
Korea.Long$lag.value = lag[1]
Korea.Long$mortality.value = mortality[1]
#loop to populate the rest

for(i in 1:5){

  for (j in 1:5){
    #skip for step
    if (!(i==1 & j==1)) {temp = Estimated.Infections.Country(Confirmed,Deaths,"Korea, South",NA,lag[i],mortality[j])
    temp$lag.value = lag[i]
    temp$mortality.value = mortality[j]
    Korea.Long = rbind(Korea.Long,temp)}
  }  
}

ggplot(Korea.Long, aes(x= Date, y= Count, group=Statistic )) +   geom_point(aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + theme(legend.position="bottom") + labs(title="COVID19- South Korea - Deaths, Confirmed Cases, Estimated Infections - Varying Mortality Rates and Lag days", y="Count", x="Days", caption="Data Source for confirmed cases and deaths: John Hopkins Hospital") + facet_grid(rows = vars(lag.value), cols = vars(mortality.value)) + facet_grid(vars(lag.value), vars(mortality.value))

For South Korea , It seems like Mortality Rates of 1.2% for Expected Infections seems high. We should use 1 or 1.1%. As for the Number of days 13 or 14 days of lag seem reasonable.

Deaths.US.States = Deaths.US[c(7,8,13:dim(Deaths.US)[2])] %>% group_by(Province_State,Country_Region) %>% summarise_at(colnames(Deaths.US)[13:dim(Deaths.US)[2]],sum)




#now convert into dataframe that can be used. With the function created by country
#with first 4 columns named  Province.State Country.Region  Lat Long

# add two columns Lat and Long

Confirmed.US.States[c("Lat","Long")]=0
Deaths.US.States[c("Lat","Long")]=0

#change names of first 2 columns and reorder

colnames(Confirmed.US.States)[1:2] = c("Province.State","Country.Region")
colnames(Deaths.US.States)[1:2] = c("Province.State","Country.Region")

Ncol = dim(Confirmed.US.States)[2]
Confirmed.US.States= Confirmed.US.States[c(1,2,Ncol-1,Ncol,3:(Ncol-2))]

Ncol = dim(Deaths.US.States)[2]
Deaths.US.States= Deaths.US.States[c(1,2,Ncol-1,Ncol,3:(Ncol-2))]



Country.Long = Estimated.Infections.Country(as.data.frame(Confirmed.US.States),as.data.frame(Deaths.US.States),"US","New York",13,0.011)
#ggplot(Country.Long, aes(x= Date, y= Count, group=Statistic )) +   geom_point(aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + theme(legend.position="bottom") + labs(title="COVID19 - New York - Deaths, Confirmed Cases, Estimated Infections - Assumed Mortality rate 1.1% \n Estimated Infections over last 13 days based on Linear Regression", y="Count", x="Days", caption="Data Source for confirmed cases and deaths: John Hopkins Hospital")


Future_beds= trunc(Country.Long[Country.Long$Date==max(Country.Long$Date) & Country.Long$Statistic=="Estimated_Infections","Count"]/10)
Start_Date = max(Country.Long$Date)-12
Start_Value = Country.Long[Country.Long$Date==Start_Date & Country.Long$Statistic=="Estimated_Infections","Count"]
End_Value = Country.Long[Country.Long$Date==max(Country.Long$Date) & Country.Long$Statistic=="Estimated_Infections","Count"]
Current_beds = trunc(Country.Long[Country.Long$Date==max(Country.Long$Date) & Country.Long$Statistic=="Deaths","Count"]*10)
ggplot(Country.Long, aes(x= Date, y= Count, group=Statistic )) +   geom_point(aes(color = factor(Statistic))) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", aes(color = factor(Statistic)))  + annotate(geom="text", x=max(Country.Long$Date), y=Current_beds, label=paste("Hosp Beds Curr(",Current_beds, ")*",sep=""), color="black", hjust = 1) + annotate(geom="text", x=max(Country.Long$Date), y=Future_beds, label=paste("Hosp Beds in 13 days(",Future_beds, ")*",sep=""), color="black", hjust = 1) + annotate("segment", x = Start_Date, xend = max(Country.Long$Date), y = Start_Value, yend = End_Value, colour = "blue", size=1.5, alpha=0.6, arrow=arrow()) + theme(legend.position="bottom") + labs(title="COVID19- New York - Deaths, Confirmed Cases, Estimated Infections - Assumed Mortality rate 1.1% \n Estimated Infections over last 13 days based on Linear Regression", y="Count", x="Days", caption="Data Source for confirmed cases and deaths: John Hopkins Hospital")

Close to half of expected infections are in New York. The State was set to lock down 2 weeks ago so most likely the expected number of infections is overshooting. Between 80,000 and 90,000 hospital beds (10% of Infections end in Hospitalization) will be required in New York in about 13 days (April 18th)

Now lets focus on the difference among the largest counties in terms of population in Florida

The following are part of the Miami area: Broward Miami-Dade Palm Beach

Orange -> Orlando is in this County Hillsborough -> The City of Tampa is in this county

# Confirmed.US  and Deaths.US Already have the information required.
#Will keep only the 5 counties and make changes to use same function.

Counties = c("Broward, Florida, US","Hillsborough, Florida, US","Miami-Dade, Florida, US","Orange, Florida, US","Palm Beach, Florida, US")
#will keep only necessary columns
Confirmed.US.FL5 =  Confirmed.US[Confirmed.US$Combined_Key %in% Counties,c("Admin2","Province_State","Lat","Long_",colnames(Confirmed.US)[grep("^X",colnames(Confirmed.US))])]

#do the same for Deaths
Deaths.US.FL5 =  Deaths.US[Deaths.US$Combined_Key %in% Counties,c("Admin2","Province_State","Lat","Long_",colnames(Deaths.US)[grep("^X",colnames(Deaths.US))])]

#Update column Names
colnames(Confirmed.US.FL5)= c("Province.State","Country.Region","Lat","Long",colnames(Confirmed.US.FL5)[grep("^X",colnames(Confirmed.US.FL5))])

colnames(Deaths.US.FL5)= c("Province.State","Country.Region","Lat","Long",colnames(Deaths.US.FL5)[grep("^X",colnames(Deaths.US.FL5))])

#charts of 5 Counties

County.Long = Estimated.Infections.Country(Confirmed.US.FL5,Deaths.US.FL5,"Florida","Broward",13,0.011)
